04484nam a22005535i 9780773570016DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20022002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735700167 a10.1515/97807735700162doi  a(DE-B1597)654465  a(OCoLC)226375907  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNK8998.U66bN88 2002eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a746.3/08/09712071931 aVon Finkenstein, Maria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNuvisavik :bThe Place Where We Weave /cMaria Von Finkenstein. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (216 p.) :bcolour illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tContributors -- t"... but I always think about the old days" -- tPanniqtuuq: Plenty of Bull Caribou -- tViews of the Past -- tTapestry: A Northern Legacy -- tThe Tapestries -- tThe Tapestry Artists -- tSuggested Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1970 a small group of young Inuit women in Pangnirtung on Baffin Island began to tell a story - a story about their past, their culture, their lives - a story told through woven pictures. The first book dedicated to the art form of tapestry weaving, Nuvisavik shows how weaving became a bridge between nomadic camp life and life in a permanent settlement. The tapestries, meticulously woven by women trained by their mothers as seamstresses, portray images wistfully remembered by elders in the community and captured by local artists. Both the drawings and the tapestries convey the pride of the Inuit in their culture. The tapestries are presented against a rich cultural and historical context. Two of the essays in the book are based on interviews with elders and reflect the colourful history of the Cumberland Sound, where sustained contact between Inuit and Americans and Scots began as early as the mid-nineteenth century. The cultural content of the tapestries is discussed by members of the Inuit community, decoding otherwise enigmatic and puzzling images. A wonderful blend of art history and cultural history, Nuvisavik will entertain the scholar and art collector as well as readers with a special interest in the history of the Canadian North. Contributors include July Papatsie, a well-established artist from Pangnirtung who brings his personal background and knowledge of his culture to his writing; Deborah Hickman, a tapestry weaver herself, who was general manager and artistic advisor to the Pangnirtung Tapestry Studio from 1980 to 1983; Cathleen Knotsch, a researcher who specializes in issues pertaining to the Canadian Eastern Arctic; and Maria von Finckenstein.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aHickman, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnotsch, Cathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapatsie, July, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVon Finkenstein, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357001640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773570016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773570016/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles